<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Germany </F>
<H3> <TI>   Number of Resettlers Reportedly Increases </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Number of Resettlers Reportedly Increases </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0104101594 Hamburg DPA in German 0917 GMT 1 Apr 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU0104101594 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bonn -- In the first quarter of 1994, the number of 
resettlers, most of whom come from Russia, has increased over 
the previous years. Speaking in Bonn on Friday [1 April], Horst 
Waffenschmidt, head of the Federal Government's agency for 
resettlers, said that during the first three months of 1994, 
49,254 resettlers have come to the FRG, 47,500 of whom are 
Germans from Russia. Over the same period of 1993, the total 
number was 44,703, while in the first quarter of 1992 it was 
47,702. 
  In March, authorities registered 16,495 resettlers, which 
was 
2,563 more than in February (13,932). Waffenschmidt emphasized, 
however, that the number of applicants wanting to resettle in 
Germany has gone down by more than 15,000 (from 72,293 in the 
first quarter of 1993 to 57,095 at the moment). Also, the 
number of people of German origin moving from Central Asia to 
German areas in western Siberia is higher than the number of 
people moving to Germany from there. In the former Soviet 
republics in Central Asia, there is "growing insecurity" among 
the Germans still living there, Waffenschmidt said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

