<F P=101> Italy &amp; Vatican City </F>
<H3> <TI>   Parliamentary Speakers Election Becoming Issue </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Parliamentary Speakers Election Becoming Issue </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR3103122094 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 1921 GMT 30 
Mar 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR3103122094 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Change Sought in Choice of </F>
Speakers"] 
  [Text] (ANSA) Rome, March 30 -- The long-standing practice 
of electing parliamentary speakers from opposition parties took 
a knock Wednesday [30 March] when the right-wing victors of 
recent elections said they would be aiming to put one of their 
own number in the speaker's chair. 
  The debate on electing speakers -- the first item on the 
agenda when the 12th legislature sits for the first time, April 
15 -- was sparked by rumours, later strongly denied, that Forza 
Italia and the National Alliance favoured centrist reformer 
[Pact for Italy leader] Mario Segni for the Lower House 
speaker's job. The rumour, said Forza Italia spokesman Antonio 
Tajani this evening, "is without any basis in fact." 
  National Alliance Secretary Gianfranco Fini, in joking mood, 
told journalists that "I would like to wait until the day after 
tomorrow before formally presenting Segni: then the Italian 
people will know it is an April Fool's trick." 
  Forza Italia chief Silvio Berlusconi, in an impromptu press 
conference this afternoon, agreed that "the concept will be of 
people from the majority parties," while Marco Taradash, the 
Pannella List-Reformers member considered close to Forza Italia, 
said "the speakers offices...must return to the governing 
parties." 
  For Francesco Speroni, the Senate whip for the Northern 
League, the opposition should not only be kept out of the 
speakers' chairs, but should not be allowed to head permanent 
parliamentary committees either. "As the League sees it, the 
winners get things now, and the losers will get things next time 
if they win," he explained. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

