<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bonn To Push Central, East Europe Entry to EU </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Bonn To Push Central, East Europe Entry to EU </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD3103154394 Berlin DDP/ADN in German 1405 GMT 31 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD3103154394 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DDP/ADN </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] Nuremburg (DDP/ADN) -- During the six months of 
its EU presidency, which begins on 1 July, Germany will be 
making efforts, in particular, for the inclusion of the Central 
and East European countries in the European Union. This was 
stressed by German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel to journalists 
in Nuremburg today. Other goals were the enlargement of the EU 
with the admission of the Scandinavian countries and Austria by 
the deadline on 1 January 1995, and employment policy at 
European level. 
  Kinkel strongly criticized the policy on Europe pursued by 
Bavarian Prime Minister Edmund Stoiber. EU "defeatism" in 
Germany was particularly uncalled for in that there was no other 
country that was as dependent on Europe as the Federal Republic. 
The FDP [Free Democratic Party] would set itself up as a "party 
for Europe" in the forthcoming election campaigns. 
  Kinkel described the outcome of the elections in Italy as 
"worrying." However, developments concerning the formation of 
the government were still awaited. Germany and France have to 
have very great interest in a rapid emergence of a stable 
government in Italy. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

