<H3> <TI>   Russian Troops Withdraw From Brocken Mountain </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Russian Troops Withdraw From Brocken Mountain </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU3103155294 Berlin DIE WELT in German 31 Mar 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> AU3103155294 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DIE WELT </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Ute Semkat report: "Russians Withdraw From Brocken"] </F>
  [Excerpts] Magdeburg -- The Gauss Point, the highest point 
on Brocken Mountain, which is 1,142 meters and thus the highest 
mountain in the Harz region, has been free of military troops 
since yesterday. After 47 years of occupation the commander of 
the Russian intelligence unit handed over the former Warsaw Pact 
monitoring post to the Federal Property Administration yesterday 
morning. [passage omitted] 
  At the official transfer ceremony yesterday 
Minister-President Christoph Bergner (Christian Democratic 
Union) stated that the departure of the Western Group of Russian 
Forces (WGT) will not be the end of relations between the 
peoples of the former Soviet Union and the Germans but the 
beginning of a new, good coexistence. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

