<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Poll Shows Pessimistic Future Expectations </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Poll Shows Pessimistic Future Expectations </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU3103153794 Berlin DIE WELT in German 31 Mar 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> AU3103153794 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DIE WELT </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [WELT-NACHRICHTENDIENST report: "Germans Expect Lean Times"] </F>
  [Text] Wiesbaden -- Germans consider Germany as a business 
location jeopardized. They also seem to be preparing for lean 
times. This is indicated by a study conducted by the Emnid 
research institute for the Chemical Industry Employers 
Association. 
  Only 4 percent of the more than 3,000 persons polled said 
that they expect prosperity to grow in the next few years. 
  According to the study, those polled think that Germany has 
dropped from first place to fourth in the listing of most 
attractive business locations. The continuing debate has led to 
growing insecurity among the people, the study says. Japan, 
Korea, Taiwan, and Singapore are considered either better off or 
the same as Germany. Only one in four puts Germany first. 
  Two-thirds of those polled (67 percent) said that Germans 
will have to work longer hours and make do with lower wages, if 
they want to meet international standards. A total of 43 
percent were convinced that German products have become too 
expensive in the international markets and are thus no longer 
competitive. Two out of three said that Germans will have to 
prepare for the growth in prosperity coming to a halt. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

