<F P=100> ITALY &amp; VATICAN CITY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Negotiations on Forming New Government </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Negotiations on Forming New Government </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0104102594 Paris AFP in English 0955 GMT 1 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0104102594 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Arcore, Italy, April 1 (AFP) - Key talks on forming 
Italy's new government between mediate magnate Silvio Berlusconi 
and aides to his nominal election ally Umberto Bossi failed to 
get under way here as scheduled Friday [1 April] morning. 
  The meeting between Berlusconi, head of the Forza Italia 
party, and a delegation from Bossi's federalist Northern League 
was due to start at 10:00 a.m. (0800 GMT) at the media magnate's 
residence in this town near Milan. 
  Berlusconi's spokesman Antonio Tajani told hordes of 
journalists at the scene that "the meeting will not take place 
here. I can add nothing more other than to say that 
negotiations are continuing and everything is going well." 
  Meanwhile Roberto Maroni, the head of the League's 
parliamentary group, said on radio that the meeting would take 
place Friday morning, but at a secret location away from media 
attention. 
  The confusion over arrangements for the meeting followed a 
statement Thursday by the League challenging Berlusconi's claim 
the premiership. 
  The federalist movement said in a statement that "the 
Northern League is the premier political force in the country," 
claiming the right to run Italy's next government. 
  The statement confirmed deep-seated rivalries between the 
two 
parties, allied with the neo-fascist National Alliance in the 
right-wing coalition which won the elections Sunday and Monday. 
  A day earlier the League had reportedly agreed to let 
Berlusconi become prime minister. 
  The League has threatened to split the rich, industrialized 
north from the rest of Italy if more autonomy is not granted to 
the regions. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

