<F P=100> CYPRUS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Lamb Concludes Visit, Leaves for Athens, Ankara </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Lamb Concludes Visit, Leaves for Athens, Ankara </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC0104103094 Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network in Greek 0900 GMT 1 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC0104103094 </F>
<F P=104>  Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network </F>

<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Robert Lamb, the U.S. State Department's special 
coordinator on the Cyprus issue, said the United States will 
continue to work hard toward both sides in Cyprus accepting the 
confidence-building measures. In a statement made this morning 
before leaving for Athens and Ankara, Lamb said significant 
progress has been made. He added that just a few problems 
remain, but he believes they can be resolved. 
  Asked whether responsibilities will be attributed for the 
deadlock, Lamb said the problem is not responsibility or which 
side will receive more advantages over the other. He said: The 
issue is to break the deadlock and find a solution. 

</TEXT>

