<F P=100> CYPRUS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Denies Turkish Claim on Training Camps </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Denies Turkish Claim on Training Camps </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC3103200294 Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network in Greek 1900 GMT 31 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC3103200294 </F>
<F P=104>  Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network </F>

<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Turkish side is trying to create tensions in 
Cyprus following the final deadlock in the proximity talks due 
to the intransigent stance maintained by Rauf Denktas. The 
fabrication of false reports about the existence of camps for 
the training of Kurdish guerrillas in Troodos is part of this 
attempt. According to CyBC's [Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation] 
reliable information, the Attila [Turkish troops in Cyprus] and 
pseudostate forces have been placed on a state of alert in order 
to make an impression. 
  A competent government source told CyBC this evening that 
the 
Turkish claims about the existence of camps for the training of 
Kurds in the free areas of Cyprus are absolutely unfounded. The 
source also stressed that these are fabrications that aim at 
serving Turkish propaganda and diverting public attention from 
the Turkish side's responsibility for the deadlock in the 
proximity talks. The same source recalled that in the past 
Turkish propaganda also tried to present Cyprus as a center for 
the training of Armenian commandos. If the Turks have any 
evidence, the source stressed, let them submit such evidence to 
the United Nations for investigation. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

