<H3> <TI>       IAEA: DPRK Could Be Isolated by Nuclear Stance </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    IAEA: DPRK Could Be Isolated by Nuclear Stance </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0104150294 Paris AFP in English 1435 GMT 1 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0104150294 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bucharest, April 1 (AFP) -- North Korea's 
unwillingness to allow inspections of its nuclear installations 
could leave the country very isolated, the International Atomic 
Energy Agency [IAEA] warned in the Romanian capital Friday [1 
April]. 
  "Without nuclear transparency, there will not be confidence 
in the outside world, and I'm sure isolation will increase if 
there is a lack of confidence in their nuclear programme," IAEA 
director general Hans Blix said Friday at a press conference 
during a four-day visit to Romania. 
  The warning, the latest during a long standoff on the issue, 
came after the UN Security Council Thursday urged Pyongyang to 
allow international inspections of suspect nuclear facilities, 
saying the Vienna-based IAEA should report back on compliance. 
  Foreign observers fear that the country, one of the last 
hardline communist regimes, is developing a military nuclear 
capability under the cover of its energy programme. 
  Blix said that if North Korea responded favourably to the UN 
request, he was ready to take up inspections again if they could 
be carried out in a "thorough" manner. "I hope they will be 
ready to do it," said Blix. 
  Allowing IAEA access was not a "privilege" to the Agency but 
a "service" to the country which would allow it to dispel 
suspicions, he added. 
  During a mission at the start of March, IAEA experts were 
stopped from taking samples at a radiochemical laboratory in 
Yongbyon, around 100 kilometres (60 miles) from Pyongyang. 
  In Tokyo, French Foreign Minister Alain Juppe dismissed 
North 
Korea's attitude over inspections of its nuclear installations 
as "unacceptable." 
  Juppe, who raised the issue in talks with Prime Minister 
Morihiro Hosokawa, told a press conference that Pyongyang's 
attitude was "unacceptable and greatly increased the risk of 
(nuclear) proliferation." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

