<H3> <TI>   Bonn Comments on Turkish Use of German Arms </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Bonn Comments on Turkish Use of German Arms </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0204145494 Hamburg DPA in German 1038 GMT 2 Apr 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU0204145494 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] Bonn/Hamburg (DPA) -- The Federal Government 
expects that all arms supplied by Germany to Turkey will be used 
in line with bilateral agreements. This was emphasized by a 
Foreign Ministry spokeswoman in connection with the discussion 
on the use of German arms in Turkey. This means that Turkey 
must use German arms only within the framework of NATO orders, 
the spokeswoman said. This was also laid down in an exchange of 
letters between the foreign ministers of the two countries in 
1992. 
  According to Christian Democratic Union [CDU] Bundestag 
Deputy Klaus Francke, the Bundestag's Foreign Committee will 
deal with the issue on the use of German arms in the Kurdish 
conflict on 13 April. The Federal Government will subsequently 
comment on the issue, Francke said on North German radio NDR on 
Saturday [2 April]. If Turkey were to use German arms in its 
actions against Kurds, this would be a violation of the 
arrangements made with Turkey. Arms supplied within the NATO 
framework must not be used in internal conflicts. [passage 
omitted] 

</TEXT>

