<H3> <TI>   Poll Shows Businessmen Favor Berlusconi as Premier </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Poll Shows Businessmen Favor Berlusconi as Premier </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR0104124994 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 1635 GMT 31 
Mar 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR0104124994 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Businessmen Want Berlusconi Premier </F>
But With Controls Over Conflict of Interest"] 
  [Text] (ANSA) Rome, March 31 -- The majority of Italian 
businessmen believe that Forza Italia leader Silvio Berlusconi 
should be given a mandate by Head of State Oscar Luigi Scalfaro 
to form a new government, but also want guarantees set down to 
separate his political, performance from his business 
activities, according to a poll to be published by the economic 
weekly IL MONDO. 
  The poll, which interviewed 202 executives and businessmen, 
found that 38.7 percent wanted President Scalfaro to give a 
mandate to Berlusconi, while 30.4 preferred someone close to the 
winning alliance forged by the owner of Fininvest but more 
independent. The choice of National Alliance head Giancarlo 
Fini as premier was the choice of 10.1 percent of those 
interviewed, while 3.6 percent indicated Northern League leader 
Umberto Bossi. 
  Berlusconi was preferred more by businessmen, while company 
executives indicated other solutions. 
  A total of 34.5 percent of those interviewed saw as "very 
realistic" Forza Italia's program, which included lowering 
taxes, more jobs and the privatization social services. Another 
13.7 percent saw it as "realistic enough." This opposed to 
33.9 percent, almost all executives, who saw it as "not very 
realistic," and 14.9 did not think it was at all realistic. 
  Those in favor of specific guarantees to separate 
Berlusconi's business and political interests, such as the 
institution of a blind trust, accounted for 64.9 percent of 
those interviewed. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

