<H3> <TI>   Interior Ministry Announces Decline in Crime </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Interior Ministry Announces Decline in Crime </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR0104124794 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 1548 GMT 31 
Mar 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR0104124794 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Crime Rate Falls, Especially in </F>
South"] 
  [Excerpt] (ANSA) Rome, March 31 -- The rise in Italy's 
crime rate came to a sudden halt in 1993, with murders down by 
27 percent and robberies by 2.9 percent, and major improvements 
in the south, according to Interior Ministry figures released 
Thursday [31 March]. 
  The number of murders committed in southern regions fell by 
301 to 736 last year, against a drop of just 89 in the rest of 
the country. 
  The southern regions remain, however, at the top of the 
charts as far as murders per 100,000 people go, with Calabria 
boasting six, and Sicily five. On a province level, Reggio 
Calabria comes in first with 12 slayings per 100,000 people. 
  Robberies were also down in the south, falling 32.4 percent 
in the north-western region of Val D'Aosta, 18.6 percent in the 
southern Calabria region, and 7.5 percent in Sicily. 
  Sicily still leads the field as far as robberies are 
concerned, however, with 137 per 100,000 inhabitants. Puglia 
follows, with 65. Forty-seven percent of all Italian robberies 
took place in the south. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

