<H3> <TI>   Regions Warn Government of Health Care Deficit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Regions Warn Government of Health Care Deficit </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR0104124894 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 1554 GMT 31 
Mar 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR0104124894 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Regions Forecast Rising Health Care </F>
Deficits"] 
  [Text] (ANSA) Rome, March 31 -- The government continues to 
underestimate financial needs for regional health care spending 
and the sector's deficit, now at more than eight trillion lire 
(five billion dollars), will probably double by the end of this 
year, according to a report released Thursday [31 March] at the 
State-Regional Conference. 
  The new government, said the report, will have to face yet 
another financial "emergency," that of inaccurate estimates for 
regional health care needs and the subsequent overspending. The 
regions want the next executive to calculate needs according to 
"realistic" data but "without imposing balanced state finances 
as a pre-requisite." 
  They want the government to identify the level of health 
care 
services that can be provided with existing resources and want 
regions to be given greater independence in levying and 
collecting health taxes. Among the proposals forwarded by the 
conference was to link regional per-capita income averages to 
spending standards and to have part of the national health care 
funds set aside for the poorer regions. 
  Figures for 1992 and 1993 show deficits in regional health 
care finances of 2.632 and 6.093 trillion lire respectively, for 
a total 8.725 trillion lire (5.25 billion dollars). The 
shortfall for this year, according to the report, will be some 
two trillion lire higher last year's, or 8.290 trillion lire 
(4.99 billion dollars), because spending will amount to 90 
trillion lire instead of the 81.71 trillion lire forecast by the 
government. 
  The criteria used by the government to make its estimates, 
said the report, "are not totally realistic or acceptable," and 
will lead to a drop in health care standards. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-18313 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu064_e_94001" </HT>


