<F P=100> UNITED KINGDOM </F>
<H3> <TI>   Sinn Fein Urge Government Response to Cease-Fire </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Sinn Fein Urge Government Response to Cease-Fire </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0304161794 London PRESS ASSOCIATION in English 1610 GMT 3 
Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0304161794 </F>
<F P=104>  London PRESS ASSOCIATION </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Chris Parkin, Chris Moncrieff, and Teilo Colley, PRESS </F>
ASSOCIATION] 
  [Excerpt] Sinn Fein leaders Gerry Adams and Martin 
McGuinness both called on the government today to respond to the 
"potential" offered by this week's IRA ceasefire. 
  Mr Adams said the three-day ceasefire from Tuesday [29 
March] 
created the opportunity to remove the stalemate that had 
developed around clarification of the Downing Street 
declaration. Its significance lay "in the potential it 
creates," he told a rally in Belfast. The British Government 
had brought about a stand-off in the peace process and "erected 
a roadblock around the issue of clarification." Now, the 
ceasefire initiative provided the chance "for Sinn Fein and the 
London government to remove the clarification roadblock so that 
the peace process can move forward." 
  "We are not concerned to force a public climbdown by John 
Major," said Mr Adams. "We will be flexible. But we will not 
accept anything less after 25 years of hard, relentless 
struggle, than the right of our supporters to be treated like 
all other citizens. We ask for no more or no less." 
  Mr McGuinness, speaking in Dublin, told supporters "the 
potential of the IRA's initiative must not be underestimated." 
It was a "significant and unprecedented initiative" which had 
created a substantial opportunity to move the situation "out of 
the current stalemate and on to the next phase of the peace 
process." 
  Mr McGuinness said: "This is the beginning, not the end of 
the process. We in Sinn Fein have asked for meaningful 
discussions with the British Government. Discussion and 
dialogue are essential elements in any peace process." [passage 
omitted] 

</TEXT>

