<F P=100> FRANCE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Poll Shows Majority Dissatisfied With Government </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Poll Shows Majority Dissatisfied With Government </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0104161694 Paris AFP in English 1550 GMT 1 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0104161694 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Paris, April 1 (AFP) -- For the first time since 
Edouard Balladur became prime minister a year ago, a majority 
(54 percent) of Frenchmen do not believe the conservative 
government is moving in the right direction, a survey showed. 
  The survey, carried out after local elections last weekend 
and due to appear in the PROFESSION POLITIQUE magazine dated 
April 8, shows a 10 percent rise in dissatisfaction with the 
government since a similar survey carried out at the beginning 
of March. 
  In the intervening period, there has been criticism of his 
handling of plans to cut the minimum wage for young people which 
led to a wave of violent protests across France. 
  The survey was carried out among a representative sample of 
805 adults contacted by telephone on Monday [28 March]. 
  It found that the government's rating fell fastest among 
right-wing voters (from 82 to 69 percent) while his rating among 
people with left-wing sympathies remained practically unchanged 
at 18 percent. 

</TEXT>

