<F P=100> ITALY &amp; VATICAN CITY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Lawyer Says Fini's Praise of Mussolini Illegal </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Lawyer Says Fini's Praise of Mussolini Illegal </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0204190394 Paris AFP in English 1828 GMT 2 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0204190394 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Rome, April 2 (AFP) -- An Italian lawyer lodged a 
formal complaint Saturday [2 April], alleging that comments by 
neo-fascist leader Gianfranco Fini praising former dictator 
Benito Mussolini are against Italian anti-fascist laws. 
  Giosue Calabria, a barrister in the central northern city of 
Bologna, claims the comments that Mussolini was "the greatest 
statesman of the this century" breach a 1952 law banning any 
public apology of fascism. 
  Calabria said the 1952 law could lead to prosecutions 
against 
"anyone who publicly exults the officials, the principles, the 
facts or the methods of fascism," and should therefore apply to 
Fini's comments. 
  Fini, whose National Alliance was in the three-party 
rightwing coalition which swept to a landslide victory in 
historic general elections on March 27-28, made the comments in 
an interview published Friday. 
  In the daily LA STAMPA newspaper, Fini said Mussolini was 
"the greatest statesman of this century," adding that Silvio 
Berlusconi, whose Forza Italia dominates the winning alliance, 
was no match for Il Duce. 
  "Berlusconi will have to run hard to show he is part of 
history like Mussolini," he said in the interview. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

