<F P=100> GREECE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Nimetz Departs; Papandreou Comments on FYROM </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Nimetz Departs; Papandreou Comments on FYROM </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC0104180194 Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network in 
Greek 1500 GMT 1 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC0104180194 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] Matthew Nimetz, President Clinton's special 
envoy on the Skopje [The Former Yugoslav Republic of 
Macedonia--FYROM] issue, has left Athens for the United States. 
According to a statement by the U.S. Information Service, Mr. 
Nimetz has drawn the conclusion that both sides desire a 
relationship based on cooperation and mutual respect for each 
other's independence and territorial integrity, and they also 
admit the dangers to stability in the region if the dispute 
continues. However, the statement points out that the 
differences between the sides are complicated and not easy to 
overcome. The statement further stresses: Mr. Nimetz will 
submit a report to Washington, present his views to UN mediator 
Cyrus Vance, and continue his efforts to support the 
negotiations within the UN framework. Mr. Nimetz will return to 
the region when this is deemed appropriate. [passage omitted] 
  Prime Minister Andreas Papandreou expressed the hope that 
there is progress on the Skopje issue before his visit to the 
United States. He noted this in response to a correspondent's 
question while he was going to the meeting of the PASOK 
[Panhellenic Socialist Movement] Central Organizing Committee. 
Mr. Papandreou described the initiative by President Clinton's 
special envoy Matthew Nimetz as positive but pointed out that 
[FYROM President] Kiro Gligorov remains intransigent and 
pressure should be exerted in this direction. 
  Government spokesman Evangelos Venizelos described the U.S. 
side's initiative toward resolving the Skopje issue as 
successful and serious. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

