<F P=100> GREECE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Papandreou Claims Balkan Crisis `Triggered' by EU </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Papandreou Claims Balkan Crisis `Triggered' by EU </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC0204143894 Athens ATHENS NEWS in English 2 Apr 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> NC0204143894 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens ATHENS NEWS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Prime Minister Andreas Papandreou has strongly 
attacked Greece's EU [European Union] partners and the Vatican. 
Departing briefly from a prepared speech yesterday, he accused 
them of having triggered a crisis in the Balkans, of which the 
Skopje [The Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia--FYROM] issue 
was only an extension. 
  Addressing the organising committee for a PASOK [Panhellenic 
Socialist Movement] party congress later this month, Mr 
Papandreou said: "We want to remind everyone that the drama of 
Yugoslavia is the creation of the European Union, particularly 
Germany and the Vatican...Europe should recognise that Greece is 
its furthest eastern point, to understand our pending national 
issues and especially our role in the Balkan region, whose 
crisis has sorely tried efforts to forge a common EU foreign 
policy. We Greeks know this better than anyone else." 
  On Skopje, Mr Papandreou stressed: "We hope the EU would 
understand that we are forced to defend our national interests 
the best way we can." 
  The premier's remarks coincided with U.S. envoy Matthew 
Nimetz' return to Washington. The Greek and Skopje foreign 
ministers will meet separately with UN mediator Cyrus Vance in 
New York on April 11. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

