<F P=100> GREECE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Spokesman Denies `Massing' Troops on Border </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Spokesman Denies `Massing' Troops on Border </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC0104205594 Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network in 
Greek 1500 GMT 1 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC0104205594 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Government spokesman Evangelos Venizelos described 
as unfortunate, unsubstantiated, and a very bad example of 
journalism yesterday's THE WASHINGTON POST report in which, 
among other things, journalist (Dean Falkland) referred to an 
excessive massing of Greek troops on the border with Skopje [The 
Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia--FYROM]. 
  Mr. Venizelos stressed that he was struck by the lack of 
historical basis in the text and how far away it was from the 
actual facts. It is obvious to everyone who has an elementary 
knowledge of the area and its history, Mr. Venizelos noted, that 
Greece is the basic guarantor of security, stability, and 
normalcy in the southern Balkans. It is well known, the 
government spokesman added, that Greece is the most friendly 
state toward Skopje; this is proven by our proposals submitted 
to Cyrus Vance on finding a solution to the problem. 

</TEXT>

