<F P=100> GREECE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reaction to `Threats' Against Istanbul Patriarchate </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reaction to `Threats' Against Istanbul Patriarchate </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC0204183594 Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network in 
Greek 1700 GMT 2 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC0204183594 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Threats by Islamists against the Istanbul 
Patriarchate have caused a chain reaction. The government has 
talked about an attempt to create artificial tension and the 
official opposition leader today called for lodging a demarche 
with Turkey. Our correspondent Roula Kambouryianni has the 
following report: 
  [Begin recording] [Kambouryianni] Official opposition leader 
Miltiadhis Evert today said: Any new aggressive action against 
the patriarchate must be considered by Greece as casus belli, 
that is a cause for war. Mr. Evert called upon the government 
to lodge a demarche and seek action by the World Council of 
Churches. 
  [Evert] On the verge of the 21st century, it is not possible 
that similar actions are taking place in any part of the world, 
no matter how backward it may be. 
  [Kambouryianni] Commenting on Evert's statement, government 
spokesman Evangelos Venizelos pointed out that the patriarchate 
knows very well how to conduct intrachurch relations. He added 
that the Greek Government's absolute support for the 
patriarchate is a given fact. Mr. Venizelos further noted that 
the initiative by Archbishop Iakovos [of North and South 
America] to brief U.S. President Clinton on the issue falls 
within the same framework. The government spokesman then 
recalled the historic presence and international status of the 
patriarchate and stressed that many circles in Turkey are trying 
to cultivate a climate of artificial tension between the two 
countries. 
  Commenting on the Islamic provocations against the 
patriarchate, Public Order Minister Stilianos Papathemelis 
emphasized today that a firm answer is needed from our side. 
The Ecumenical Patriarchate and Patriarch Vartholomeos have 
become the target of the Islamist municipal authorities. 
Islamist Mayor of Istanbul [name indistinct] said: I will pass 
through the "gate of hatred." He meant the patriarchate gate 
that has been closed since 1821 when [Patriarch] Grigorios V was 
hanged there. The Istanbul mayor added that he will not allow 
the revival of the Byzantine state that the patriarch allegedly 
seeks. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

