<F P=100> CYPRUS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Rejects Discussion of UN Documents </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Rejects Discussion of UN Documents </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC0204124994 Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network in Greek 1030 GMT 2 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC0204124994 </F>
<F P=104>  Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network </F>

<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Government has stressed that it is not willing 
to have any further discussions of the informal UN documents, 
because Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktas has not accepted 
them. Government spokesman Ioannis Kasoulidhis said any further 
discussions or an extension of the deadline would be 
counterproductive if there is no Turkish political will to reach 
a solution. Kasoulidhis was commenting on a statement by a U.S. 
official to the Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation [CyBC] that he 
expects the Turkish side to be given two weeks to reply. 
  Kasoulidhis said the Cypriot Government expects the UN 
secretary general's report to be submitted in accordance with UN 
Security Council Resolution 902. He stressed that the report 
should fully describe the facts, which speak for themselves. He 
said there is no indication that the report and its conclusions 
is a temporary measure. 
  In his statement to CyBC, the U.S. official said that if the 
Turkish side continues its negative stance after the two-week 
deadline, the UN Security Council will consider alternative ways 
to implement its resolutions. The U.S. official said Robert 
Lamb, the U.S. State Department's special coordinator on the 
Cyprus issue, intends to discuss with the Turkish Government 
ways to overcome the latest obstacles. According to the same 
official, the basic obstacle is access to Famagusta. On this 
issue, Denktas demands satisfaction regarding who will guard the 
access and from what distance. The U.S. official said that 
eight of the 70 issues that Denktas asked clarification on are 
still pending. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

