<F P=100> CYPRUS </F>
<H3> <TI>   UN Awaits Turkish Response on Confidence Measures </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    UN Awaits Turkish Response on Confidence Measures </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC0404180594 Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network in Greek 1600 GMT 4 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC0404180594 </F>
<F P=104>  Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network </F>

<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The United Nations awaits the results of the 
contacts of Robert Lamb, U.S. State Department special 
coordinator on Cyprus, in Ankara before making public the UN 
secretary general's report to the UN Security Council [UNSC] 
regarding the talks on the confidence-building measures. A U.S. 
official told Apostolis Zoumbaniotis, CyBC [Cyprus Broadcasting 
Corporation] correspondent in New York, that the UN secretary 
general's report is expected to finally be given to the Security 
Council tomorrow. 
  The CyBC correspondent also reports that all indications are 
that the Turkish side will be given 15 days to accept the 
latest proposals of Joe Clark, the UN secretary general's 
special representative for Cyprus, regarding the means of 
implementing the confidence-building measures. The CyBC 
correspondent reports the possibility of the Security Council 
putting substantial pressure on the Turkish side is very slight 
due to strong objections by the United States. 
  Security Council circles told the CyBC correspondent that it 
can not be ruled out that after the expiration of the 15 day 
time limit, President Glavkos Kliridhis and [Turkish Cypriot 
Leader] Rauf Denktas will be invited to go to New York, either 
to sign an agreement or for a coordinated effort to find a 
compromise with the participation of the UN secretary general 
and the five permanent members of the Security Council. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

