<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kinkel Urges North Korea To Open Nuclear Sites </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kinkel Urges North Korea To Open Nuclear Sites </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0404177494 Berlin DDP/ADN in German 1700 GMT 4 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0404177494 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DDP/ADN </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Berlin (DDP/ADN) -- German Foreign Minister Klaus 
Kinkel has called upon North Korea to open its nuclear 
installations immediately to inspections of the International 
Atomic Energy Agency. He was very concerned about North Korea's 
continuing refusal to meet its obligations under the nuclear 
Nonproliferation Treaty, Kinkel told the daily newspaper DIE 
WELT (Tuesday [5 April] edition). Any state's violation of the 
treaty was a serious danger to world peace. 
  As a state which had renounced the production of ABC 
[atomic, 
biological, chemical] weapons under international law, Germany 
supported the nonproliferation of all weapons of mass 
destruction. In this connection, Kinkel referred to his 
suggestion of a worldwide cooperative policy of nonproliferation 
of 15 December 1993. Kinkel said that he strongly supported the 
unlimited extension of the nuclear nonproliferation treaty, 
which was due for renewal in 1995. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

