<F P=100> GREECE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Cypriot, Greek Parliamentarians Hold Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Cypriot, Greek Parliamentarians Hold Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC0404164494 Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network in 
Greek 1500 GMT 4 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC0404164494 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The respective presidents of the Greek and Cypriot 
Parliaments, Apostolos Kaklamanis and Alexis Galanos, met in 
Athens today and discussed close cooperation and better 
coordination between the two institutions to promote national 
issues. During the meeting there was a mutual briefing 
regarding the difficulties in support for national issues in 
international organizations. 
  Kaklamanis stated that besides the issue of Skopje [The 
Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia, FYROM], the Cyprus issue 
is also at a critical phase as a result of the talks on 
confidence-building measures. The president of the Greek 
Chamber of Deputies repeated the commitment repeatedly expressed 
by the government and prime minister to togetherness, 
solidarity, and common direction between he two countries. 
  Alexix Galanos, the Cypriot House of Representatives 
president, referred to the hypocritical practice of using 
different measures and putting different weight on the issues of 
Skopje and Cyprus. Although Turkey invaded and occupies the 
north of the island, today it appears as a peaceloving nation. 
The president of the Cypriot House of Representatives stressed 
that besides the unified defense space, Greece and Cyprus should 
formulate a unified diplomatic area to promote national issues, 
which are undivided. At 1500 [1200 GMT] this afternoon, Galanos 
also met Greek Alternate Foreign Minister Theodhoros Pangalos. 
  After meeting Galanos, Pangalos said they discussed topics 
regarding Cyprus, developments around the Cyprus issue, and the 
Cypriot Parliament's participation in the Parliamentary Assembly 
of the Council of Europe. 
  Asked to comment on developments in Istanbul, Pangalos said: 
We have a series of developments that concern us and we have 
the statement of the new mayor. I hope calm will prevail and 
that someone will prove to those who use such methods that they 
should choose between a return to the past and a move to the 
future. Turkey cannot possibly seek a position in the family of 
European nations and, at the same time, remember the 
achievements of the captors [reference to the Ottoman Empire]. 
I believe that Hellenism, the civilized world, and the great 
community of Orthodox nations, Pangalos concluded, are 
determined to protect the Orthodox Partriarchate, which is an 
international organization with particular importance for the 
world community as a whole. 

</TEXT>

