<F P=101> Germany </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kinkel Outlines FDP Priorities in Election Campaign </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kinkel Outlines FDP Priorities in Election Campaign </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0504133994 Hamburg DPA in German 1157 GMT 5 Apr 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU0504133994 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bonn -- The leader of the Free Democratic Party of 
Germany [FDP], Klaus Kinkel, has again called on the members of 
his party to make the independence of liberal policies clearer 
vis-a-vis the Christian Democratic Union/Christian Social Union 
[CDU/CSU] and the Social Democratic Party of Germany [SPD] 
during the upcoming election campaigns. "Whereas the 
conservatives and the SPD used to be worlds apart, Labor 
Minister Bluem and SPD social affairs expert Dressler are 
congenial brothers," Kinkel stated in the party organ LIBERAL 
DISPATCH (April edition). 
  The FDP leader spoke in favor of more privatization and 
deregulation in the economy. As a "counterforce" to the Greens, 
the FDP must clearly support nuclear energy as a "transitional 
energy," it must promote biotechnology and genetic engineering, 
and reject general speed limits, Kinkel pointed out. Moreover, 
his party should "vigorously advocate its role as the party 
ensuring the rule of law" and support performance elites in 
Germany. 
  It is particularly important "for the FDP to be noticed both 
because of what it does and because of the way it does things," 
Kinkel continued. Credibility and style have become central 
political messages. "Politicians may make mistakes, but they 
cannot afford everything," the FPD leader stressed. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

