<F P=101> Germany </F>
<H3> <TI>   Industry President Rejects Fast EU Enlargement </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Industry President Rejects Fast EU Enlargement </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0404174494 Hamburg DPA in German 1129 GMT 4 Apr 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU0404174494 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Munich (DPA) -- Hans-Peter Stihl, president of the 
Federation of German Chambers of Industry and Commerce [DIHT], 
has warned against rushing the enlargement of the European Union 
[EU] toward the East. The economic differences between the EU 
countries and the former East Bloc countries, such as Poland or 
Hungary, are still dramatically big, Stihl said on Bavarian 
Radio on Easter Sunday. In the next 10 years it will be 
unthinkable to accept these countries as full members into the 
EU. Until then, such a development could be initiated through 
associate membership agreements. 
  Moreover, the EU must now gather its strength for the 
planned 
enlargement by another four countries. Over the next few years, 
the EU will be tied up with creating an economic, and maybe even 
a political, community. With a view to Brussels, Stihl 
criticized the EU's interventionism in trade issues. Bilateral 
agreements with individual countries, such as the recent new 
agreement with Japan on car exports, would encumber free trade, 
Stihl concluded. 

</TEXT>

