<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Germany </F>
<H3> <TI>   Lamers: Halting Arms to Turkey Not `Sufficient' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Lamers: Halting Arms to Turkey Not `Sufficient' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0604081394 Hamburg DPA in German 2037 GMT 5 Apr 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU0604081394 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Osnabrueck (DPA) -- The Christian Democratic Union 
[CDU]/Christian Social Union [CSU] does not think that halting 
arms deliveries to Turkey, which is no longer ruled out by 
Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel (Free Democratic Party), either, 
is a sufficient response to the basic problem of the 
relationship between Turkey and the West. In an interview with 
NEUE OSNABRUECKER ZEITUNG (Wednesday edition), Karl Lamers, 
foreign policy spokesman of the CDU/CSU Bundestag group, 
stressed that membership in the European Union, which Turkey is 
striving for, is becoming increasingly impossible in view of 
Turkey's way of dealing with the Kurdish problem. 
  Of course, it would place a serious strain on German-Turkish 
relations if it could be proved that German weapons are used 
against the Kurds. From the moral point of view and because of 
the Turkish Government's promise to the contrary, it would then 
certainly be justified to stop arms deliveries. On the other 
hand, Germany would thus give up any possibility to influence 
Turkey and its behavior toward the Kurds. Therefore, the 
Kurdish problem can be solved only by political means, by having 
us and others convince Turkey that there cannot be any solution 
without, at least, far-reaching cultural autonomy. "The 
excessive use of weapons against parts of the Turkish people is 
a bad thing -- no matter where the weapons come from," Lamers 
stressed. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

