<H3> <TI>   Union Asks for Protection of Media in Kurdistan </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Union Asks for Protection of Media in Kurdistan </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0504201194 Hamburg DPA in German 1612 GMT 5 Apr 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU0504201194 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Stuttgart (DPA) -- The Media Trade Union has 
reacted with dismay to the assassination of German journalist 
Lissy Schmidt. A statement of the Main Executive Board on 
Tuesday [5 April] says that, according to the trade union's 
information, Schmidt investigated inroads of the Turkish 
military and intelligence service on the territory of northern 
Iraq. The 35-year-old photographer, member of the Media Trade 
Union, and her Kurdish companion had been shot in an ambush in 
the northern Iraqi part of Kurdistan on Sunday. 
  The Media Trade Union appealed again to the Turkish 
Government to guarantee the protection of journalists who 
exercise their occupation in Kurdistan and their free and 
unhindered reporting. It called on the Foreign Ministry in Bonn 
to request the Turkish Government to observe the freedom of the 
press. 

