<H3> <TI>   Defense Minister on NATO's 45th Anniversary </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Defense Minister on NATO's 45th Anniversary </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR0504153294 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 1754 GMT 2 
Apr 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR0504153294 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "NATO: Fabbri on 45th Anniversary </F>
of Alliance"] 
  [Text] (ANSA) Rome, April 2 -- Today marks the 45th 
anniversary of the Atlantic Pact, the signing of which united 
the nations of Western Europe and of North America in their 
determination "to defend freedom and democracy from the looming 
threat of a new totalitarianism", Italian Defense Minister Fabio 
Fabbri wrote in a message to the Armed Forces on this occasion. 
  After underscoring that this Atlantic choice had created "a 
community of ideals and of interests which allowed our nations 
to progress in prosperity and in security", Fabbri added that 
the European nations, "lacerated by war, found in NATO a 
decisive element for overcoming ancient divisions and for 
establishing strong mutual confidence". 
  For Fabbri, even in the new European geo-political context 
which, he stressed, to a great extent was itself "the fruit of 
Atlantic policies in the face of the totalitarianism's 
challenges", NATO has confirmed its "indispensable role of 
defense and as a factor of security and peace". 
  He recalled the fundamental contribution made by the accords 
for nuclear and conventional disarmament, the stabilizing 
effects of the opening to the new democracies of central and 
eastern Europe, and the missions carried out in Bosnia and in 
the Adriatic for the United Nations. 
  The Italian armed forces, which for four decades have been 
an 
active and dedicated part of the Atlantic military instrument, 
will continue to provide their decisive contribution to NATO, 
taking part in the common defense and in peace missions, Fabbri 
continued in his message. Furthermore, those Atlantic values 
which were at the base of Italy's choices for civilization and 
peace will find themselves ever more grounded and ever more 
suffused within Italian society, he concluded. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-18465 </DOCNO>
