<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Turkey </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ankara Denies German Weapons Used Against Kurds </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ankara Denies German Weapons Used Against Kurds </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0504140094 Hamburg DPA in German 1359 GMT 5 Apr 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU0504140094 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] Ankara/Bonn (DPA) -- On Tuesday [5 April], 
Turkey denied reports that weapons supplied by Germany are being 
used in the fight against militant Kurdish separatists. Turkish 
Foreign Ministry Spokesman Ferhat Ataman told DPA in Ankara that 
the Turkish Armed Forces do not use the German weapons in 
contradiction to bilateral agreements or their own commitments. 
Turkish Defense Minister Mehmet Golhan had also reaffirmed this 
last Friday, he said. 
  On Tuesday, in a letter to his Turkish counterpart, Hikmet 
Cetin, FRG Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel again called for the 
observation of the NATO restrictions on the weapons supplied by 
Germany. According to the Foreign Ministry, Kinkel referred to 
the "recurrent assertions by politicians and media" that the 
German weapons that were supplied according to NATO provisions 
are used, contrary to the agreement, against the banned Workers 
Party of Kurdistan (PKK). As early as on Monday, Kinkel had 
appealed to the Turkish Government to use means of the 
rule-of-law state for the prosecution of the Kurdish extremists 
and to refrain from using weapons from Germany in the fight 
against the PKK. 
  Turkish Foreign Ministry Spokesman Ataman said that the 
representatives of the German media are apparently confusing the 
BTR-60 and BTR-80 armored personnel carriers that had been 
bought in Russia with the vehicles from the arsenals of the 
former GDR [German Democratic Republic] People's Army supplied 
by Germany. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

