<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Conference on Yugoslavia To Reduce Staff </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Conference on Yugoslavia To Reduce Staff </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0504185594 Paris AFP in English 1832 GMT 5 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0504185594 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Geneva, April 5 (AFP) -- The co-chairmen of the 
Geneva conference trying to restore peace in the former 
Yugoslavia are planning to reduce its staff as mediation bids 
are being undertaken elsewhere, diplomats said here Tuesday [5 
April]. 
  Lord Owen of the European Union and Thorvald Stoltenberg of 
the United Nations will axe the posts of two Swedish military 
advisers. It is also unlikely that spokesman John Mills will 
still be in his job after the end of the month. 
  Diplomats said two United Nations Protection Force 
[UNPROFOR] 
liaison officers may soon be recalled from Geneva. A decision 
will ultimately have to be made by French General Bertrand de 
Lapresle, UNPROFOR chief commander in Croatia. 
  "There is no political determination to do away with the 
conference," said a European diplomat who declined to be 
identified, but peace mediators are aware of the fact that the 
Geneva talks are suspended for the time being. 
  Parties to the conference -- Bosnian Serbs, Croats and 
Moslem 
government officials -- last broke up on February 12 after no 
progress was made in three days of talks on the makeup of three 
ethnic states in Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  But since that date negotiations held under the auspices of 
the United States and Russia have ended Serb shelling of 
Sarajevo, settled the territorial dispute between Bosnian Croats 
and Moslems, and yielded a ceasefire accord between Croatia and 
Croat Serb separatists. 
  Geneva conference working groups on ethnic minorities and on 
economic issues have not met for some time. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

