<F P=100> FRANCE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Balladur Urges Inclusion of Workers' Rights in GATT </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Balladur Urges Inclusion of Workers' Rights in GATT </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0504120394 Paris AFP in English 1146 GMT 5 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0504120394 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Paris, April 5 (AFP) -- France has urged inclusion 
of workers' rights and environment committees in the future 
World Trade Organisation (WTO), to be created after ratification 
of the Uruguay Round of GATT global trade talks in Morocco, next 
week. 
  Premier Edouard Balladur wrote to European leaders arguing 
that the two issues should come within the compass of the WTO, a 
communique by Industry Minister Gerard Longuet said. 
  The communique, released after a ministerial meeting chaired 
by Balladur, said the WTO should "deal with issues affecting 
international trade such as the environment and workers' rights." 
  Setting up an environment committee has already been agreed, 
but many countries, in particular developing countries, are 
opposed to creation of a committee on social issues, including 
workers' rights. 
  In the communique, Longuet said it was Europe's duty "to 
promote economic and social development and to defend human 
rights, in particular those of the individual at work" when 
setting up international trade rules and mechanisms. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

