<F P=100> FRANCE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Minister Denies Receiving Cannabis From Farmers </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Minister Denies Receiving Cannabis From Farmers </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0504152094 Paris AFP in English 1502 GMT 5 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0504152094 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] L'Isle-Jourdain, France, April 5 (AFP) -- Militant 
farmers have given home-grown cannabis to French Agriculture 
Minister Jean Puech, saying cultivating the drug was the only 
way they had of making a living. 
  The gift was "produced by a French farmer" as his "only way 
of feeding his family," said a communique released in this 
southwestern French town, headquarters of the activist group 
Rural Coordination. 
  In Paris, Puech denied receiving a parcel of cannabis from 
the farmers. "If such a parcel reached me, I would immediately 
hand it over to the police." 
  Criticising the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade, the 
farmers' communique said low world prices had forced Third World 
farmers to produce drugs. 
  "By accepting the ratification of GATT, Mr. Puech has opted 
for a world of unemployment, violence and drugs. Farmers will 
adapt their crops to this," the communique said. 
  The gift of cannabis was made to mark the end of Puech's 
first year as minister, the communique said. 
  More than 120 countries will sign the new GATT in Marrakesh, 
Morocco, on April 12-15. 

</TEXT>

